            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
                My mom and dad were born and grew up in small towns in southern Utah, my dad in Henrieville and mom in Cannonville. My mom was a school teacher and my dad worked on ranches when they met and eventually married in a civil ceremony and they were sealed in the St. George temple in 1908 and my oldest brother Rhoe was sealed to them at that time. A second child Maude lived only a few months. <br /><br />

                My parents then moved to Idaho where they hoped to find better employment and lived in southeastern Idaho for the remainder of their lives. Twin girls, Melba and Nelda, along with Frant, Duard, Ruby, Dean, Ethel, Bart, and Carma were added to the family and raised to adults. <br /><br />

                    My dad was a man who was honest, a hard worker to provide for his large family. He mostly worked as a cattle herder for ranchers and was always held in esteem by his employers as a good and hard worker. He later was employed by Bonneville County as the foreman on the county road and bridge crew and has been instrumental in the building of many of the bridges in Bonneville County. His example of “an honest day's work” has carried on to his family, each of whom he taught the importance of hard work and fulfilling responsibilities given. <br /><br />

                    The large family was raised during the depression years and necessitated the need for the adult children to find work to help support the family. I have often heard from my older siblings that the family was a very happy family with much love and respect for each other. There was not jealousy or competition among them and if any one of them happened to receive or attain a gift or reward or special attention in one way or another there was never any jealousy or bad feelings among the others. I have often heard my brothers and sisters say, “We had so little that when any one of us was on the receiving end of something special we were all happy for that sibling.” <br /><br />

                    My mother was a stay-at-home mom and always had the welcome mat ready and welcome for anyone who needed help or attention. She was an excellent cook and very talented in “making do” with what she had. She was especially known for her delicious bread rolls which she always had ready for anyone. Mom was a quilt maker and once told me she had probably made 50 or 60, all hand-quilted. Her home was always warm and comfortable even though she raised her children in times of distress because of the depression years. <br /><br />

                    She and my dad lived in Sugar City for a number of years and then moved to Idaho Falls, on Whittier Street where I was born. We then lived on F Street for several years across the street, Memorial Drive, from the LDS hospital. We then moved south to 16th Street. I lived there with my parents through the 2nd grade to high school graduation. My mom was a “Four Star Mother” during the Second World War, as she had four sons who served in the military and a plaque from the government was proudly displayed in the front window of our home indicating such.
