                    One very vivid occurrence at the hospital will always be etched into my memory. When my sister, Melba’s little girl Sharlene was eight or ten months old she got pneumonia and was in the hospital for several days. On one of those days I rode my bicycle up to the hospital and looked up to the floor and the window of the room where Sharlene’s bed was and could see my mother and my sister standing at the window crying and I knew then that my little niece had died. She was a beautiful little girl with lots and lots of black hair and big black eyes. My dad used to call her “my little papoose.” <br /><br />

                    In 1931, I began school at the Riverside Elementary School at the age of five. Memories are few from the first grade but I do remember having a traumatic experience there. Our teacher had given us instructions that anyone who whispered on that particular day would have their mouth taped. I was “tricked” into turning around in my seat when Polly Fitch (I even remember her name) poked me and whispered something and I did tum around but didn't utter a word. But I was accused and convicted on the spot by the teacher and my mouth was taped! Very embarrassing to me. <br /><br />

                    I attended school there for the first grade and then my parents moved to 187 E. 16th Street in Idaho Falls where I attended school at the East Side Elementary School building. There are a few memories of the East Side building. I believe it was three stories high and had dark wood floors and a wide stairway leading to the upper floors. There were big round drinking fountains in the center of the foyer of each floor. There was a big grassy area field outdoors where we played soccer during recess. I also remember the restrooms at that school because that is where I would roll my long stockings down to my ankles and tuck a hated “garter belt” which was used to hold up the stockings. I hated the heavy long stockings which Mom put on me to wear during the cold winter months. <br /><br />

                    Every so often when I am near to a school classroom, there are special memories that come floating back of those early grade school rooms with the smell of the blackboard, the erasers and the smell of the dark hardwood floors that were treated with a waxy substance with a very strong odor—not necessarily unpleasant but very strong and memorable. The house on 16th Street was an unusual building. At one time it had been lived in while still just a basement. Later when we moved into it, it consisted of the down stairs which was a kitchen and a dining sort of room, a bathroom and a coal room. Up a narrow and dark flight of stairs was a living room where the front door to the house was at street level and also two bedrooms. <br /><br />

                    My memories of that house at that time consist of a pot-bellied stove in one comer and windows on the north, east and south of the room. The bedrooms were off a foyer sort of area. I remember small closets in that house. I remember my dad drying his long underwear in the winter time which were hung on that pot-bellied stove! I also have memories of when we would listen to drama on the radio, The Lone Ranger, The Shadow, and of course, The Hit Parade, which was the list of the 10 most popular tunes at that time. There were lots of big trees around the place. The backyard was a little lower than the front and so sloped off to the north. <br /><br />

                    My parents always had a garden. There was an alley that ran through most blocks at that time where garbage cans were kept to be picked up later by a truck. I also remember a big tree in the back and a run-down building in the back of the lot where a car was kept. Also there was, for the first years we lived there, a sort of corral. I can’t remember what animals were kept there but I do remember the old bam of sort; it was small. There was also a water hydrant near the northwest of the house where the hoses were attached for the outside watering. <br /><br />

                    I also remember my dad hanging a mutton from the big tree in the back and it was taken down and the meat cut off as needed. I don’t know what might have kept it from spoiling but I remember my dad always had a mutton somewhere for us to eat. (I grew up hating mutton!) The coal room which was opposite the bathroom in the back hallway was a dark and scary place. Before we got a furnace, which was many years after we moved there, the coal would be ordered and dumped through the upper window of the room where it could be put into buckets and carried to the cook stove in the kitchen or up the stairs to the stove in the living room. <br /><br />

                    We had a round oak table which was used for serving meals, and the kitchen stove was a huge black thing, which had to be fed coal or wood for cooking and heating water. I remember my mom heating water in a big copper oblong kettle on the stove for laundry and other errands. The sink was in the comer of the kitchen, the windows were high and we could only see the sky from them. <br /><br />

                    In the summer time the old coal bin was cleaned out and miraculously became my play room. Not very much light in there but nevertheless it was mine for a few short months! In the fall when the leaves from those big tree were feeling we would gather them up in huge piles and then dive into them with much joy. We also made houses of them by raking them into rooms and with much pretending could often become a castle! In the area of Idaho Falls during those early growing up years on 16th Street, we were surrounded on many sides by vacant lots; there were few houses then. The neighborhood kids and I had lots of fun playing in those vacant lots and later when some of had bicycles we would ride over the fields and through the dirt roads with great glee. We would also use our sleds in the winter (there used to be lots more snow then than we have now) and ride down the hills in the area. <br /><br />

                    A branch of the Idaho Canal ran just a half block south of our house and we often swam in it during the summer…it seemed so much larger than it actually is now as we drive by on 17th St, We would swim down that stream toward Reno Park as it was called then (Tautphaus now) and get out at the potato chip factory and get some sacks of their broken chips which we were given free and then walk through the Rose Hill Cemetery (we weren’t allowed to swim through the cemetery) and then float again on down to Reno Lake. A great deal of Tautphaus Park today used to be Reno Lake.<br /><br />

                    I was baptized at eight years on the 20th of January, 1935 by Glen I. Wilkinson in the fount at the First Ward chapel, it being the stake building at that time. I clearly remember coming up out of the water and being confirmed a member of the church while I was still wet. I was confirmed by John Homer. I have a very special memory of the day President Heber J. Grant visited the Third Ward. I remember looking up into his face as I shook his hand and what a thrill it was. I also remember that when he walked into the chapel everyone stood up as we still do today when a prophet enters the room. Also, all the ladies were asked to remove their hats!
            </span>

