                    As long as I can remember, I have loved beans! All kinds of beans! And I hated cottage cheese when I was a kid. One memory I have is of a meal with all the family around and someone helped me take up my plate with food and of all things most terrible they put some beans on my plate and then plopped cottage cheese right on top of the beans. It was terrible and I went crying away from the table because of the tragedy and it just made me sick! Later on I grew to love cottage cheese—interesting what we remember! <br /><br />

                    My mother always made biscuits out of some of her bread dough when she made a big batch of bread and they weren’t small rolls; they were huge and they raised up to be beautiful big rolls and she continued to make them until just a few months before she died at 95. <br /><br />

                    Another incident that I have always remembered about myself and my mother was when one time she was stirring a batch of fudge to thicken it up, and I kept standing beside her and dipping my finger into the pan to taste it and—fudge being a favorite of mine—I just kept at it until she pushed my whole hand down into the pan! It was a little warm still so I yelped and immediately began to wash it off. She was quite disturbed at me and said, “Why are you washing it all down the sink when you wanted it so bad!” The old-time fudge recipes had to be cooked to a certain point and then beat until thick…not like the newfangled recipes that almost immediately become fudge—but it is really good as well, attesting to Kristen Mary and all the fudge she has made for me over the years—thank you, Kristen Mary! 
